<div id="review_2426855166" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2426855166" />
    <a title="Michael" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/32804270-michael"><img alt="Michael" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1564311252p2/32804270.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2426855166?book_show_action=true">Sep 08, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Michael" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Michael" href="/user/show/32804270-michael">Michael</a>
      </span>

          added it


          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780679741954" href="/book/show/381359.The_Death_and_Life_of_Great_American_Cities">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/32804270-michael?shelf=2019">2019</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2426855166" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15706588264900894651">Impassioned, if dated, <i>The Death and Life of Great American Cities</i> sets out to catalogue the conditions that make a large city diverse, safe, and vibrant. Jacobs begins her work by critiquing modernist urban planning as pseudo scientific and dangerously out of touch with reality, before she turns to examining why and how some city neighborhoods prosper while others decline. Focusing mainly on New York, her home, the author offers great insight into what makes urban life teem with vitality, and t</span>
  <span id="freeText15706588264900894651" style="display:none">Impassioned, if dated, <i>The Death and Life of Great American Cities</i> sets out to catalogue the conditions that make a large city diverse, safe, and vibrant. Jacobs begins her work by critiquing modernist urban planning as pseudo scientific and dangerously out of touch with reality, before she turns to examining why and how some city neighborhoods prosper while others decline. Focusing mainly on New York, her home, the author offers great insight into what makes urban life teem with vitality, and then repeats those insights over and over; she’s also short on policy suggestions, and her analysis fails to fully account for the role race plays in housing, gentrification, and disinvestment. The prose is alternately tedious and moving—the sections in which Jacobs describes street life shine, as do those that first build her thesis.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15706588264900894651" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


