<div id="review_143208150" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/143208150" />
    <a title="Tamara" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4748847-tamara"><img alt="Tamara" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1302018083p2/4748847.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/143208150?book_show_action=true">Jan 24, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tamara" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tamara" href="/user/show/4748847-tamara">Tamara</a>
      </span>

          added it




        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4748847-tamara?shelf=non-fiction">non-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4748847-tamara?shelf=geography">geography</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4748847-tamara?shelf=north-america">north-america</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4748847-tamara?shelf=usa">usa</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4748847-tamara?shelf=urbanist">urbanist</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4748847-tamara?shelf=economics">economics</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4748847-tamara?shelf=author-female">author-female</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4748847-tamara?shelf=new-york">new-york</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4748847-tamara?shelf=library-wants-things-back-sometimes">library-wants-things-back-sometimes</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4748847-tamara?shelf=race">race</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer143208150" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15674135961705751176">Finally finished! I think Jacobs has retained a reputation for a certain cosy New-Urbanist kitchiness, and that&apos;s sadly unfair. <br/><br/>The first few chapters, with their endless gushing lyricization of the &quot;urban ballet&quot; romantic descriptions of rows of stores on some Greenwhich village street did have my teeth mildly on edge. (They put me in mind of nothing so much as one of George RR Martin&apos;s descriptive passages of food or flags.) However, moving past that, her underlying view of the city is actuall</span>
  <span id="freeText15674135961705751176" style="display:none">Finally finished! I think Jacobs has retained a reputation for a certain cosy New-Urbanist kitchiness, and that's sadly unfair. <br /><br />The first few chapters, with their endless gushing lyricization of the "urban ballet" romantic descriptions of rows of stores on some Greenwhich village street did have my teeth mildly on edge. (They put me in mind of nothing so much as one of George RR Martin's descriptive passages of food or flags.) However, moving past that, her underlying view of the city is actually considerably more heardheaded, even jaded - intriguingly and refreshingly. <br /><br />Rather than celebrating the density and diversity of cities as some fuzzy invitation to endless communality, she actually praises the sharp deliniation of privacy and withdrawl allowed by the city, explains the economic basis of functional streets and emphasizes the changeability of spaces and the inevitable influence of built form on use and community.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15674135961705751176" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
