  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/568215098" />
    <a title="Jennifer Richardson" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/13169543-jennifer-richardson"><img alt="Jennifer Richardson" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1348675786p2/13169543.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/568215098?book_show_action=true">Mar 22, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jennifer Richardson" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jennifer Richardson" href="/user/show/13169543-jennifer-richardson">Jennifer Richardson</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer568215098" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7733317198734112004">FINALLY finished this book, but it was worth trucking through because I learned so much! Urban planning is something I knew literally nothing about, and now I am able to hold a reasonably intelligent conversation about some of the issues- to the point where some nosey stranger said &quot;ahh you guys are planners aren&apos;t you?&quot; This book is surprisingly easy to read, and Jane Jacobs approaches the flaws of current urban planning tactics with amusingly caustic commentary, giving enough background to inf</span>
  <span id="freeText7733317198734112004" style="display:none">FINALLY finished this book, but it was worth trucking through because I learned so much! Urban planning is something I knew literally nothing about, and now I am able to hold a reasonably intelligent conversation about some of the issues- to the point where some nosey stranger said "ahh you guys are planners aren't you?" This book is surprisingly easy to read, and Jane Jacobs approaches the flaws of current urban planning tactics with amusingly caustic commentary, giving enough background to inform but not overwhelm, and then often moves into a well organized explanation of what she believes is a better approach. I highly recommend this to anyone who lives in a city and is interested in why things around them seem to play out the way they do and want to be more in touch with the complex inner-workings of the city itself. And a plug- to hell with Radiant Garden City Beautiful!</span>
  <a data-text-id="7733317198734112004" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

<tr class="no_border feedFooterReview" id="update_comment_stuff_Review568215098">
