    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_4242914148" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4242914148" />
    <a title="Jacques de Villiers" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/78943976-jacques-de-villiers"><img alt="Jacques de Villiers" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1616057944p2/78943976.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4242914148?book_show_action=true">Dec 29, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jacques de Villiers" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jacques de Villiers" href="/user/show/78943976-jacques-de-villiers">Jacques de Villiers</a>
      </span>

          added it


          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover 9780679600473" href="/book/show/499475.The_Death_and_Life_of_Great_American_Cities">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/78943976-jacques-de-villiers?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4242914148" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10985220393131066982"><i>It is so easy to blame the decay of cities on traffic…or immigrants…or the whimsies of the middle class. The decay of cities goes deeper and is more complicated. It goes right down to what we think we want, and to our ignorance about how cities work.</i><br/><br/>I wake up grateful to live in a world in which so many brilliant books exist. Some entertain or inform or shatter me. But perhaps the ones I value the most are those that ‘rewire’ me, fundamentally changing my perception of some deep facet of everyda</span>
  <span id="freeText10985220393131066982" style="display:none"><i>It is so easy to blame the decay of cities on traffic…or immigrants…or the whimsies of the middle class. The decay of cities goes deeper and is more complicated. It goes right down to what we think we want, and to our ignorance about how cities work.</i><br /><br />I wake up grateful to live in a world in which so many brilliant books exist. Some entertain or inform or shatter me. But perhaps the ones I value the most are those that ‘rewire’ me, fundamentally changing my perception of some deep facet of everyday existence. Jane Jacobs’s astonishing treatise on cities is one such book. I can’t walk down streets or drive through neighbourhoods without this book rubbing itself off on my vision. It is a love letter to cities, as well as a rude and revolutionary correction as to what exactly makes cities vital and innovative places to live. And as if this weren’t enough, unlike innumerable critics of the status quo, Jacobs doesn’t just evaluate and critique. She actually has solutions for making cities better! <br /><br />Even though some parts get relatively technical, this is not only a book for architects or city planners. Everyone who lives in cities should read it.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10985220393131066982" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

